detail: precision of the coordinate pair (precise or approximate)
label: localisation precision
notes: The precision is relative to the class of the Location. E.g., it is expected that if the coordinates have localisation precision "precise" and the class is “settlement”, the coordinates will fall within the area of the (medieval) settlement. But for a Location with class “house”, “precise” would mean that it is precisely localized at the granularity of houses! This means that a medieval house will rarely have localisation precision precise; rather, it will either be localized to the settlement, one of its gates or one of its parishes, and the localisation precision will be “approximate”, or there will be no coordinates but a location relation stating that the gate is “SRP next to” it or that the house has as its “superordinate location” the settlement. A church will often have localisation precision "precise", since its location is often known or it is still standing.
